How it works and what to watch for:
The Pmod model is edge-driven, not time-driven. It loads a fresh packet on every CS falling edge and shifts one bit per SCLK falling edge. That's deliberate — it means the model stays correct no matter what DELAY_COUNT you use, and more importantly, it only stays in sync with the DUT if the DUT produces exactly 40 SCLK periods per transaction with clean CS framing. If your byte/bit counters don't reset between transactions, the model and DUT drift apart and you'll see it as a wrong reading.
Three transactions with distinct data is the actual test. I picked values that are easy to spot: 300/600/btn=5, then 1023/0/btn=2, then 512/511/btn=7. If everything resets cleanly each cycle, all three pass. If something accumulates (a counter not wrapping, bit_tc getting stuck, shift_cntr off by one), transaction 0 might pass but 1 or 2 will mismatch — which is exactly the "falls out of sync over time" failure you're worried about. The asserts fire on any mismatch, and the report line prints actual vs expected so you can see how it's wrong (a bit-shifted value tells you something different than a totally scrambled one).
Two caveats:

The TB assumes you've made DELAY_COUNT a generic. If you skip that, delete the generic map line and the sim will still run, just much slower (the 375-tick delays stretch each transaction to ~2ms).
The sample-point fix is mainly a hardware robustness thing. In simulation, delta-cycle ordering may let even the old boundary-sampling version pass, because the simulator doesn't model real hold-time. So don't read a passing sim as proof the boundary version was fine — the fix is still worth keeping for the board. The TB's real value here is catching framing/counter desync, which it does either way.

One thing to confirm separately from this TB: the actual SPI mode of the real Pmod (I modeled Mode 0). The Digilent example code will tell you which edge it drives data on. If it turns out to be different, you'd flip the model's falling_edge(spi_sclk) to rising_edge and possibly adjust SAMPLE_POINT.
